<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="46" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,258,858]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,727,751]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pruthi. A" authorityYear="1930" box="[671,858,726,750]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Gurawa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minorcephala">
<emphasis box="[671,858,726,750]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">G. minorcephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
externally, but can be distinguished by the longer style preapical lobe (
<figureCitation box="[384,469,762,786]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,249,1368,1391]" captionTargetBox="[199,1390,182,1345]" captionTargetId="figure-240@6.[188,1398,169,1371]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Gurawa truncata sp. nov. A: male pygofer side, lateral view; B: valve and subgenital plate, ventral view; C: style, dorsal view; D: connective, dorsal view; E &amp; F: aedeagus, dorsal and lateral view, respectively." pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
) and shape of the aedeagal shaft (
<figureCitation box="[849,970,762,786]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,249,1368,1391]" captionTargetBox="[199,1390,182,1345]" captionTargetId="figure-240@6.[188,1398,169,1371]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Gurawa truncata sp. nov. A: male pygofer side, lateral view; B: valve and subgenital plate, ventral view; C: style, dorsal view; D: connective, dorsal view; E &amp; F: aedeagus, dorsal and lateral view, respectively." pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Figs 3E–F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="46" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,258,858]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,333,799,823]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin word “truncata” referring to the shape of the aedeagal apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1941,1999]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,268,1941,1964]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">PLATE II.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Duan &amp; Zhang, 2012" authorityName="Duan &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2012" box="[274,449,1942,1964]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Gurawa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[274,449,1942,1964]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Gurawa truncata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[455,535,1942,1963]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[455,535,1942,1963]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
A: habitus, dorsal view; B: habitus, lateral view; C: face; D: the end of female abdomen, ventral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
